[[File:Negev Brigade Memorial1.JPG|thumb|Negev Brigade Memorial]] [[File:Beersheba, Monument to Negev Brigade, Bunker 01.jpg|thumb|Negev Brigade Memorial]] [[File:Monument to the Negev Brigade 113.jpg|thumb|Negev Brigade Memorial]] [[File:Monument to the Negev Brigade 108.jpg|thumb|Negev Brigade Memorial]] [[File:Oc1-אנדרטת חטיבת הנגב.jpg|alt=|thumb|Negev Brigade Memorial]] The '''Monument to the Negev Brigade''' ({{lang-he|אנדרטת חטיבת הנגב}}, ''Andartat Hativat HaNegev''), known locally as the '''Andarta''', is a monument designed by [[Dani Karavan]] in memory of the members of the [[Palmach]] [[Negev Brigade]] who fell fighting on [[Israel]]'s side during the [[1948 Arab Israeli War]]. It is situated on a hill overlooking the city of [[Beersheba]] from the east and constitutes a recognized symbol of the [[Negev]] and Beersheba. In addition to its strengths as a memorial, it was a precursor to the [[land art]] movement.<ref>Klaus Honnef, Manfred Schneckenburger, Christiane Fricke, and Karl Ruhrberg. ''ART of the 20th Century.'' Taschen. 2000. Pg. 544.</ref>
The monument was built between 1963 and 1968 at a time when Israel was making many physical memorials to those who fought and died in its wars.<ref>Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs. [http://www.mfa.gov.il/MFA/Facts+About+Israel/Culture/CULTURE-+Visual+Arts.htm ''CULTURE: Visual Arts.''] 1 Oct 2006 - accessed on 5 January 2007.</ref> It is made of raw concrete consisting of eighteen separate elements covering 10,000 square meters. These elements are symbolic and connected to Palmach and to the War of Independence.
The perforated tower alludes to a watchtower shelled with gunfire and the pipeline tunnel is reminiscent of the channel of water in the Negev defended by the soldiers. Engraved in the concrete are the names of the 324 soldiers who died in the war,<ref>Israel Ministry of Defense. [http://www.izkor.gov.il/AndartaNames.aspx?id=81001 ''Names of the Fallen''] 2010 - accessed on 15 November 2007.</ref> the badge of the Palmach, diary passages from the soldiers, the battle registry, verses (from the Bible 2 Kings 2:12<ref>in Hebrew: "My father! My father! The chariots and horsemen of Israel!"</ref>) and songs.
