{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Use British English|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox book | name = Mortality | image = Cover of Mortality by Christopher Hitchens, Atlantic 2012.jpg | caption = The cover of the [[Atlantic Books]] hardcover first edition | author = [[Christopher Hitchens]] | country = United States | language = English | subject = Biography | publisher = [[Hachette Book Group United States|Twelve Books]] (US), [[Atlantic Books]] (UK) | pub_date = 1 September 2012 | media_type = Hardcover, Paperback, Audiobook, eBook | pages = 160pp [[Hachette Book Group United States|(Twelve)]], 128pp [[Atlantic Books|(Atlantic)]] | isbn = 978-1-4555-0275-2 | oclc = 776526158 }}
'''''Mortality''''' is a 2012, posthumously published book by Anglo-American writer [[Christopher Hitchens]], comprising seven essays which first appeared in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' concerning his struggle with oesophageal cancer, with which he was diagnosed during his 2010 book tour<ref>Bowcott, Owen (1 July 2010) [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/01/aurtho-christopher-hitchens-diagnosed-cancer "Author Christopher Hitchens diagnosed with cancer"] from ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref> and which killed him in December 2011.<ref>Grimes, William (16 December 2011) [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/16/arts/christopher-hitchens-is-dead-at-62-obituary.html?_r=0 "Christopher Hitchens, Polemicist Who Slashed All, Freely, Dies at 62"] in ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> An eighth chapter consisting of unfinished "fragmentary jottings," a foreword by [[Graydon Carter]], Hitchens' ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' editor and an afterword by Carol Blue, Hitchens' widow, are also included in the publication.<ref>Buckley, Christopher (30 August 2012) [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/02/books/review/mortality-by-christopher-hitchens.html?pagewanted=all "Review of ''Mortality'': Staying Power"] in ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>
== Description ==
Hitchens held the post of contributing editor at ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' from November 1992 until his death.<ref>[[Christopher Hitchens]] contributor page at [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|''Vanity Fair'']]: http://www.vanityfair.com/contributors/christopher-hitchens</ref> In this capacity he contributed about 10 essays per year on subjects as diverse as politics and the limits of self-improvement, writing about "anything except sports".<ref>Hitchens, Christopher (2012). Mortality. Atlantic Books Ltd., p.103 {{ISBN|978-1-4555-0275-2}}</ref> Therefore, he felt obliged when he was asked to write about his illness for the magazine, and managed to dispatch seven essays from "Tumourville" before he was overcome by his illness on 15 December 2011, aged 62.<ref>Grimes, William (16 December 2011) [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/16/arts/christopher-hitchens-is-dead-at-62-obituary.html?_r=0 "Christopher Hitchens, Polemicist Who Slashed All, Freely, Dies at 62"] in ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> The essays take as their subject matter his fear of losing the ability to write, the torture of chemotherapy, an analysis of [[Nietzsche]]'s proclamation that "what doesn't kill you makes you stronger," the joy of conversation and the very meaning of life.<ref>Hitchens, Christopher (2012). Mortality. Atlantic Books Ltd. {{ISBN|978-1-4555-0275-2}}</ref>
== Critical reception == The critical response to ''Mortality'' was largely positive with friends and admirers of Hitchens praising both his character in confronting his death and the way that this was transferred onto the page. In a glowing review of ''Mortality'' in ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]] described Hitchens' seven essays as "diamond-hard and brilliant" and "word-perfect." He wrote that it was "sobering and grief-inducing to read this brave and harrowing account of his "year of living dyingly" in the grip of the alien that succeeded where none of his debate opponents had in bringing him down." Buckley was a friend of Hitchens.<ref>Buckley, Christopher (30 August 2012) [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/02/books/review/mortality-by-christopher-hitchens.html?pagewanted=all "Review of ''Mortality'': Staying Power"] in ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> [[Colm Tóibín]] fondly wrote in ''[[The Guardian]] ''of his experiences with Hitchens, opining that "he was the best company in the world" and offered praise for ''Mortality'', writing that "in this book he does everything to make sure that his voice remains civilised, searching and ready to vanquish all his enemies, most notably in this case the dullness of death and its silence."<ref>Tóibín, Colm (31 August 2012) [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/31/mortality-christopher-hitchens-review "''Mortality'' by Christopher Hitchens – review"]'' ''in ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref> In ''[[The Observer]] ''[[Alexander Linklater]] was also complimentary. Referring to [[John N. Gray|John Gray's]] description of Hitchens as "one of the greatest living writers of English prose",<ref>Gray, John (6 October 2011) [http://www.newstatesman.com/books/2011/09/hitchens-trotsky-convictions "Review: ''Arguably'' by Christopher Hitchens"]'' ''in ''[[New Statesman|The New Statesman]]''</ref> Linklater responded that "the only word of that which is certainly untrue is that Hitchens is now no longer living." He also noted: "The real struggle in ''Mortality'' is not with mortality. Hitchens cleaves to the logical conclusion of his materialism. He hints, rather, at a fear of losing himself, of becoming an imbecile, someone who might, in terror and pain, say something foolish or (God forbid) religious near the end, to give his enemies satisfaction. The true struggle of his last writings is to remain himself, deep in the country of the ill, for as long as he can."<ref>Linklater, Alexander (26 August 2012) [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/26/mortality-christopher-hitchens-review "''Mortality'' by Christopher Hitchens – review"] in ''[[The Observer]]''</ref> Another positive review came from the magazine where Hitchens started his career, ''The New Statesman''. George Eaton wrote that Hitchens' final work had "a timeless, aphoristic quality".<ref>Eaton, George (7 September 2012) [http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/culture/2012/09/mortality-christopher-hitchens-–-review "''Mortality'' by Christopher Hitchens – review"] in ''[[New Statesman|The New Statesman]]''</ref>
